  "texts": [
    "C. The Scaling Plane: A Unified View of ElasticityThis work introduces the Scaling Plane, a model where each configuration of a distributed database is represented as a point (H, V), where H is the number of nodes and V = (c, r, b, s) is a vector of per-node CPU, RAM, bandwidth, and storage characteristics.",
    "We derive the following surfaces over this plane:• node-intrinsic latency surface,• coordination/consensus latency surface,• throughput surface with diminishing returns, • coordination overhead surface, • monetary cost surface,• aggregate objective surfaces combining the above.",
    "arXiv:2511.21612v1 [cs.DC] 26 Nov 2025 We show that these surfaces are neither monotonic nor separable in H and V. Instead, their minima lie along interior valleys reachable by joint scaling actions.",
    "D. Diagonal Scaling: A Missing AbstractionWe reveal that optimal scaling paths frequently follow diagonal directions-scaling both H and V together.",
    "Diagonal scaling outperforms both:• pure scale-out (horizontal-only),• pure scale-up (vertical-only)."
  ],
